Code 
#In this data frame, "dap" stands for "days after planting" with 4 levels: 120, 130, 140, 150

rm_rcbd_df <- read_csv("../data/wheat_nk_balkh_rm.csv") %>%
  mutate(across(trt:splot, ~factor(.))) %>%
  mutate(fdap = factor(dap)) #fdap = dap as factor #because we want to have "dap" as both numeric and categorical columns

#1st argument in across() function: select all columns between "trt" and "splot" #2nd argument: ~factor(.) here . is a place holder into which all selected columns (trt:splot) are passed

7.3.3 Block random effects are iid ~ N(0,var_a)

Code 
ranef(mod3_gen)[[1]] %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sample=`(Intercept)`))+
  stat_qq(  shape = 21,
            fill = "purple", 
            size = 3,
            alpha = .7
  )+
  stat_qq_line()+
  labs(x = "Theoretical quantile",
       y = "Sample quantile",
       title = "General Model: Blocks Random Effects QQ plot")+
  theme_bw()
Code 
ranef(mod1_default)[[1]] %>% 
  ggplot(aes(sample=`(Intercept)`))+
  stat_qq(  shape = 21,
            fill = "purple", 
            size = 3,
            alpha = .7
  )+
  stat_qq_line()+
  labs(x = "Theoretical quantile",
       y = "Sample quantile",
       title = "Default Model: Blocks Random Effects QQ plot")+
  theme_bw()

Interpretation: In the QQ plot shown above, we have only 4 data points since there are only 4 blocks. Taking that into consideration, the residuals appear to fall closely around the QQ line with no strong curvature pattern and there is no huge deviations from the tail points to the QQ line. Hence, the residual normality assumption appears to hold.

Visual comparison of residuals between default and general model: For the random effect associated with Block, the residuals in the QQ plot of the default model appear to be very v-e-r-y similar (if not the same) to those of the general model QQ plot.

Code

Interpretation of model assumptions:

Residual independence:

From the fitted vs.Â residual plot shown above, we see:

  • no clear pattern of residuals
  • random cloud of points of residuals
  • the error band for the smooth line comprises of 0 along the x-axis

Hence, the residual independence assumption appears to hold.

Residual homogeneous variance/ variance homogeneity/ homoscedasticity:

From the fitted vs.Â residual plot shown above, we see:

  • spread of residuals seems to be even along y-axis
  • spread of residuals seems constant (i.e., neither increasing nor decreasing) along x-axis
  • no clear pattern of residuals
  • random cloud of points of residuals
  • the error band for the smooth line comprises of 0 along the x-axis

Hence, the residual homogeneous variance/ variance homogeneity/ homoscedasticity assumption appears to hold.

Outlier detection:

From the fitted vs.Â residual plot shown above, we see that all residuals fall within [-3, 3] interval along the y-axis. Hence, there is no outlier present to skew the model interpretation.

Visual comparison of residuals between default and general model: For the fitted vs.Â residual plots shown above, the residuals in the fitted vs.Â residual plot for the default model appear to be very v-e-r-y similar to those of the fitted vs.Â residual plot for the general model.

Answer:

For the âmod1_defaultâ i.e., default model, the 3-way âkrate_kgha:nrate_kgha:fdapâ interaction (p-value = 0.06951) is not significant at Alpha = 0.05 significance level, rather the 2-way âkrate_kgha:nrate_kghaâ interaction (p-value = 1.047e-06) and the âfdapâ main effect (p-value < 2.2e-16) are significant at Alpha = 0.001 significance level. Hence, we would mention 2 different pairwise letter separation plots/tables/interpretation paragraphs: one for the 2-way âkrate_kgha:nrate_kghaâ interaction, and another plot/table/interpretation paragraph for the âfdapâ main effect (because both âkrate_kgha:nrate_kghaâ and âfdapâ were significant at Alpha = 0.001 significance level).

In contrast, the âmod3_genâ i.e., general model had the 3-way âkrate_kgha:nrate_kgha:fdapâ interaction (p-value = 7.576e-05) to be highly significant at Alpha = 0.001 significance level. Hence, we would extract means and mention pairwise letter separation plots/tables/interpretation paragraphs either to compare different days after planting (fdap) within all combinations of nitrogen rate and potassium rates, or to compare all combinations of nitrogen and potassium rates within each day after planting (fdap) â depending on our research question/interest.
